# ReText Extension ŌĆö Project Rules

## Architecture

This is a Manifest V3 Chrome/Edge extension with four main components:

- **content.js** ŌĆö Injected into every page. Walks the DOM (`Node.TEXT_NODE`), applies replacements, and re-runs via `MutationObserver` on dynamic content.
- **popup.js / popup.html / popup.css** ŌĆö The extension popup UI. Table-based list of rules, modal for add/edit, search bar, global toggle, import/export.
- **background.js** ŌĆö Service worker. Manages badge count, context menu, broadcasts toggle messages to all tabs.
- **manifest.json** ŌĆö Declares permissions (`storage`, `activeTab`, `contextMenus`), content scripts, and icons.

Communication flow: popup Ōåö storage Ōåö content script, popup ŌåÆ background (badge), background ŌåÆ tabs (global toggle broadcast).

## Critical Regex Pitfalls

### 1. Never use `regex.test()` then `regex.replace()` on the same global regex

`test()` with a `/g` flag advances `lastIndex`. A subsequent `replace()` starts from that position and misses the first match. Always use `replace()` directly and compare the result:

```js
// WRONG ŌĆö skips first match
if (regex.test(text)) { text = text.replace(regex, replacement); }

// CORRECT
const newText = text.replace(regex, replacementText);
if (newText !== text) { text = newText; modified = true; }
```

### 2. `\b` word boundary does NOT work with special characters

`\b` sits between `\w` ([a-zA-Z0-9_]) and `\W`. For search terms containing `$`, `(`, `.`, `+`, etc., `\b` silently fails to match.

**Solution:** Detect special chars and use whitespace-based lookaround instead:

```js
const hasSpecialChars = /[^a-zA-Z0-9_]/.test(textToReplace);
if (hasSpecialChars) {
  pattern = `(?<=^|[\\s])${escapedText}(?=[\\s]|$)`;
} else {
  pattern = `\\b${escapedText}\\b`;
}
```

### 3. Always escape user input before building regex

```js
const escaped = text.replace(/[.*+?^${}()|[\]\\]/g, '\\$&');
```

## Scope Matching

- Empty/null/whitespace scope ŌåÆ match all pages.
- Wildcard `*` is converted to `.*` for regex. Test against both `hostname` and full URL.
- Multiple scopes are comma-separated. Any single match = pass.
- **Trailing slash matters:** `*/view/*` requires content after `/view/`. Use `*/view*` for flexible matching (matches `/view`, `/view/`, `/view?q=1`).

## Storage

- `chrome.storage.sync` can silently fail in Edge without a Microsoft account. If Edge support is critical, use `chrome.storage.local` or add fallback.
- Always check `chrome.runtime.lastError` after storage operations.
- Replacement objects have this shape: `{ textToReplace, replacementText, scope, wholeWord, enabled }`.
- `globalEnabled` is stored alongside `replacements` in the same storage area.

## Import/Export

The import function must handle three JSON formats:
1. `{ replacements: [...] }` ŌĆö standard backup
2. `{ codes: [{ code, name, scope }] }` ŌĆö codes format (scope can be a string OR array)
3. `[...]` ŌĆö plain array (either format of objects)

When `scope` is an array, join with `", "` for internal storage.

CSV uses 5 columns: `textToReplace,replacementText,scope,wholeWord,enabled`. Fields with commas/quotes/newlines must be quoted with doubled internal quotes.

## Testing Strategy

Browser APIs (`chrome.storage`, `chrome.tabs`, DOM) cannot be unit-tested in Node.js. Instead:

1. Extract pure logic into testable functions: `matchesScope`, `applyReplacement`, `filterActiveReplacements`, `searchFilter`, `computeBadgeCount`, `escapeCsvField`, `parseCsvLine`.
2. Copy those functions into `tests/test-all.js` and test with Node.js assertions.
3. Validate file structure (manifest references, required elements in HTML) via `fs` checks.
4. Run with `node tests/test-all.js`.

When adding new logic to any source file, also add the corresponding pure function + tests to the test file.

## Badge

- Active count > 0 ŌåÆ green (`#4caf50`) badge with the number.
- Global OFF ŌåÆ red (`#f44336`) badge with text "OFF".
- No active replacements ŌåÆ empty badge (hidden).

## Files to Never Commit

- `data/*.local.json` ŌĆö user-specific data (in `.gitignore`).
- `data/codes.json` committed as a template with example placeholder data only.
